SIMPLE: hiccough
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Hiccough
<hw>Hic"cough</hw> <pr>(?; 277)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>hickup</ets>, <ets>hicket</ets>, <ets>hickock</ets>; prob. of
imitative origin; cf. D. & Dan. <ets>hik</ets>, Sw. <ets>hicka</ets>,
Armor. <ets>hak</ets>, <ets>hik</ets>, W. <ets>ig</ets>, F.
<ets>hoquet</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Physiol.)</fld> <def>A modified
respiratory movement; a spasmodic inspiration, consisting of a sudden
contraction of the diaphragm, accompanied with closure of the glottis,
so that further entrance of air is prevented, while the impulse of the
column of air entering and striking upon the closed glottis produces a
sound, or hiccough.</def> <altsp>[Written also <asp>hickup</asp> or
hiccup.]</altsp>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Hiccough</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Hiccough
<hw>Hic"cough</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Hiccoughed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Hiccoughing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <def>To have a hiccough
or hiccoughs.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>hick</ent>⟦br⟧
